---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost(Astro.request.headers.get('host'));
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')); }
let valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0,12);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="bg-[linear-gradient(135deg,#f7faf5,#ecfdf5_45%,#fff)] border-b border-emerald-900/10 py-14">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="badge">{site.primaryKeyword}</span>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-4">{title}</h1>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-xl text-slate-700">{desc} The guidance below is tailored to {site.angle}.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && site.domain === 'shopifyemailmarketingapps.com' && <section class="container py-12">
    <article class="card prose-shopify">
      <h2>Shopify email marketing apps: shortlist by operating reality</h2>
      <p>There is no universal winner. A small catalog with one marketer needs a different tool from a high-volume brand with several merchandisers, multiple storefronts, and a dedicated lifecycle team. Use the table to narrow the field, then validate the claims that matter in your own store: event freshness, product-feed behavior, segment limits, deliverability controls, and the total cost of the profiles and messages you actually plan to retain.</p>
      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto not-prose">
        <table class="data-table min-w-[920px]"><thead><tr><th>App</th><th>Best fit</th><th>Pricing shape</th><th>Shopify-specific edge</th><th>Watch-out</th></tr></thead><tbody>
          {APPS.slice(0, 13).map(app => <tr><td><a class="link font-bold" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{app.name}</a></td><td>{app.bestFor}</td><td>{app.pricing}</td><td>{app.strengths[0]}</td><td>{app.limits[0]}</td></tr>)}
        </tbody></table>
      </div>
      <h2>How to run a credible pilot</h2>
      <p>Keep the pilot small enough to learn from and large enough to expose real store behavior. Connect the catalog, customer, order, and checkout events first. Rebuild only three flows: welcome, abandoned checkout, and post-purchase or winback. Hold out a comparable audience where your platform supports it, and record revenue after discounts, unsubscribe rate, deliverability, time to launch, and the number of manual fixes required. A platform that reports impressive attributed revenue but cannot explain event timing or suppress recent purchasers is not ready for scale.</p>
      <div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto not-prose"><table class="data-table min-w-[760px]"><thead><tr><th>Pilot checkpoint</th><th>Evidence to request</th><th>Pass signal</th></tr></thead><tbody>
        <tr><td>Data quality</td><td>Test orders, products, refunds, and customer properties</td><td>Events arrive with usable timestamps and product context</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Flow rebuild</td><td>Three production-shaped journeys with exclusions</td><td>Team can launch without custom work for normal cases</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Economics</td><td>Quote using retained profiles, sends, and SMS separately</td><td>Expected incremental margin still works at 2× list growth</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Reporting</td><td>Campaign, flow, segment, and holdout views</td><td>Revenue is reconciled to Shopify orders, not only clicks</td></tr>
      </tbody></table></div>
      <h2>Fast recommendation</h2>
      <p>Start with Shopify Email when the requirement is basic campaigns and the team wants the lowest operational overhead. Shortlist Omnisend or Privy when speed and approachable multichannel capture matter. Test Klaviyo or Drip when segmentation, catalog logic, and lifecycle reporting are central. Consider Sendlane, Yotpo Email &amp; SMS, or Rejoiner when migration help, a broader retention program, or strategic support justifies the extra cost. Brevo and Mailchimp can be sensible for straightforward sends, but verify Shopify event depth before making them the foundation of a behavior-heavy program.</p>
    </article>
    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-700">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-slate-950">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-semibold">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div>
  </section>}
  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && site.domain !== 'shopifyemailmarketingapps.com' && <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-700">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-slate-950">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-semibold">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container grid gap-8 py-12 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_320px]"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>What {app.name} does for Shopify stores</h2><p>{app.shopifyFit} For searches around <strong>{site.primaryKeyword}</strong>, the main question is not whether {app.name} can send campaigns. The question is whether it can use Shopify data in a way that produces better timing, cleaner targeting, and fewer margin-killing discounts.</p><h2>Where it fits best</h2><p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. It belongs on the shortlist when your store needs {site.channel} workflows connected to real order history, product interest, and customer lifecycle stage.</p><h2>Strengths</h2><ul>{app.strengths.map(s=><li>{s}</li>)}</ul><h2>Limits to watch</h2><ul>{app.limits.map(l=><li>{l}</li>)}</ul><h2>Shopify buying advice</h2><p>Choose {app.name} if its workflow depth matches your next 90 days of retention work. Skip it if the team only needs a one-off newsletter sender or if pricing forces you to suppress useful segmentation. For {site.keywordPlural}, the winning tool is the one your team will actually operate weekly.</p></article><aside class="card h-fit"><div class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-700">Snapshot</div><dl class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm"><div><dt class="font-bold">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-bold">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-bold">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl><a class="btn btn-primary mt-6 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a></aside></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a,b])=><a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-bold">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Which is better for {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()}?</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container py-12"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Shopify takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Pick based on operating model, not logo recognition.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Model costs against list growth and message volume.</td></tr><tr><td>Strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{site.primaryKeyword} should create revenue you can defend.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card"><h2>Verdict for {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{a?.name} is usually better when you need {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} is stronger when the store cares more about {b?.bestFor}. For Shopify, choose the tool that handles your highest-value lifecycle moments first: welcome, checkout recovery, post-purchase, replenishment, VIP, and winback.</p><p>If both tools look close, run a simple migration-risk test: can your team rebuild the top five revenue flows, segment by product and order history, and read revenue by campaign without manual spreadsheet work?</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-bold">{s.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Marketing problems: {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How {seg.name} should choose {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{seg.name} have to account for {seg.pain}. That changes the app shortlist: the best choice is not always the biggest platform, but the one that maps those store-specific signals into useful messages.</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,7).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Implementation notes</h2><p>Start with one money flow, one trust-building flow, and one reactivation flow. For {site.keywordPlural}, more campaigns are not automatically better. Better timing and cleaner segmentation usually beat extra sends.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-bold">{u.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Use {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()} to {u.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best approach for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}. For {site.primaryKeyword}, that means using Shopify events, product context, consent, and customer history to decide who gets the message and when.</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a>: {a.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><h2>What to measure</h2><p>Measure recovered revenue, unsubscribe rate, repeat purchase rate, margin after discounts, and revenue by segment. Avoid judging {u.name} only by opens or attributed clicks.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; const alts=APPS.filter(a=>a.slug!==app.slug).slice(0,8); return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Why Shopify stores look for {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>{app.name} is a credible option, but it is not always the right fit for every store searching for {site.primaryKeyword}. Common reasons to compare alternatives include pricing, channel mix, migration workload, segmentation depth, and how much Shopify-specific reporting the team needs.</p><h2>Best alternatives</h2><ul>{alts.map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Selection rule</h2><p>Do not switch tools just for a cleaner interface. Switch when the alternative makes an important Shopify workflow easier to launch, easier to measure, or cheaper to scale.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify app selection framework</h2><p>Pick {site.primaryKeyword} by matching your business model to lifecycle jobs. New stores need capture, welcome, cart recovery, and first purchase campaigns. Growing stores need segmentation, post-purchase education, replenishment, winback, and deliverability discipline. Larger brands need governance, experimentation, attribution, and channel coordination.</p><h2>Internal linking map</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All apps</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison pages</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Fashion store guide</a></li></ul></article></section>}
</BaseLayout>
